@Node introsnap "SnapShot Manual"
@Next "reminder"
@Prev "Main"
@Toc "Main"
 WHAT IS SNAPSHOT?

  * Did you know that today no file is safe anymore?
  * Did you know there is a lot of trojans today?
  * Do you want to protect your harddisk 100%?
  * Do you want to use a simple and effective way?


                     If yes, please read the folowing little text:
                     ---------------------------------------------

                     SnapShot is a `startup-utility` aimed at harddisk and
                     BBS users, and is a SUPPLEMENT (NOT a replacement) to
                     a  good virus checker/killer.  It can also be used by
                     floppy  users,  but  is  intended  to  be  used  on a
                     harddisk  system.   SnapShot  is  not only automatic,
                     it`s also much, much faster than a conventional virus
                     checker. Snapshot will find all kind of garbage 100 %
                     including  virus,  trojans  and infiltrator programs.
                     FUTHERMORE ..you will be able to catch >>ALL<< future
                     viruses and -trojans.  


                     IMPORTANT:  SnapShot  is excellent for bulletin board
                     purpose  as  a high-tech system watch. Do you want to
                     take a risk? If not - use SnapShot!


                     Snapshot  will  automatically check your harddisk for
                     viruses  every day, week, month or whatever intervals
                     you  decide.   If  the  disk  structure  is  not 100%
                     identical  to  what SnapShot expects to find you will
                     get  a  message  telling you that something is wrong,
                     and  you  can  do a more extensive check of the disk.
                     The  advantage  over  other virus checker programs is
                     that  SnapShot  will do this automatically, say every
                     week.  So if you forget(?) to check your harddisk for
                     viruses, SnapShot will do it for you!!


      REMARK:        SnapShot will find "ALL"...new unknown viruses too!!!


      ATTENTION:     SnapShot  is  special  very excellent for BBS purpose
                     to  avoid hacking  by  the  new very used infiltrator
                     programs,  which  enables  a hacker to take over your
                     bulletin board.
@Endnode


::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::


@Node reminder "SnapShot Manual"
@Next "quick"
@Prev "introsnap"
@Toc "Main"
AUTOMATIC BBS VIRUS TEST


                     Running  a BBS, you might want SnapShot to perform a
                     check  every  5 hours.  Now, there are three ways to
                     go about this:


                  1. You  can  reset  your  machine  every 5 hours, making
                     SnapShot  scan  your  directories,  but getting up at
                     night  to  reset your amiga is proberply not the most
                     fun you can have in the middle of the night ;-) or..

                  2. You  can - manually - every 5 hours start a shell and
                     type  in  the  command,  which  /can/ become a little
                     tiresome, OR...

                  3. You can can do this by telling a cron to run SnapShot
                     with   the   same   arguments   you   use   in   your
                     startup-sequence.


 
                     AUTOMATIC TEST USING THE "REMINDER" PROGRAM 
                      ..........................................

                     One  of  the  more  userfriendly  crons  is  Reminder
                     written  by  Ebbe  H.   Pedersen.   At  this writing,
                     version 6.0 (3-feb-95) is the most recent.


                     The  difference  between this and many other crons is
                     the  GUI,  which makes Reminder easy to use.  You can
                     then  ask  Reminder  to  start SnapShot, or any other
                     program for that matter, every five hours.


                     Refer  to Reminders manual for an installation guide.
                     The  archive  is called Reminder60.lha (62k), and you
                     should  be  able  to  find it on your local board, or
                     Aminet.
@Endnode

